      <hedline>
        <hl1>Lexington Ave. Shuttle?</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Letter from Clement Chin suggests ways to alleviate subway crowding in Manhattan without building costly Second Ave subway line (May 8 article)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>It would be nice to have a Second Avenue subway line (letter, May 8),  but the cost is high. Since the problem seems to stem from the added ridership in Manhattan, maybe something can be done to alleviate the crowding in that borough.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>It would be nice to have a Second Avenue subway line (letter, May 8),  but the cost is high. Since the problem seems to stem from the added ridership in Manhattan, maybe something can be done to alleviate the crowding in that borough.</p>
        <p>How about a shuttle service on the Lexington Avenue line? Just make it run more frequently than the existing service on that line and have it run only in Manhattan. The people in the Bronx and Brooklyn might feel shortchanged, but it would benefit them, too, because the subway would be less crowded.</p>
        <p>CLEMENT  CHIN  Woodside, Queens, May 10, 2000</p>
      </block>
